{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501103","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501103"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:23:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:23:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1720"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1720"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.39,0.49,0.05,0.01,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1720"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101718"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1720"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1720"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84174"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"265"},{"type":"tags","id":"1149"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6863"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8385"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14436"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35299"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101718"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a painless swelling in the left side of his scrotum. This has been present for about five years and he thinks it has become more noticeable. The swelling is only visible when he stands. He does not have any other symptoms. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The swelling is soft, non-tender and can be felt above the left testis, which can be identified as a separate entity. There is no cough impulse and the swelling appears to extend up into the inguinal canal. It cannot be reduced into the abdominal cavity. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance","Ultrasound of the groin and scrotum","CT of chest and abdomen","Fine needle aspiration cytology","Surgical exploration of the groin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic signs of a varicocele, which is an abnormal dilatation and enlargement of the pampiniform plexus of veins in the scrotum. Varicoceles are common, occurring in approximately 20% of the male population. In this case, given the long-standing nature of the condition and the absence of any concerning features, the most appropriate management is \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassurance\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound of the groin and scrotum\u003C/strong\u003E is generally a good non-invasive modality for evaluating scrotal pathologies and can confirm the diagnosis of varicocele. However, in this case, the clinical presentation is typical of a varicocele, and the diagnosis can be made based on the physical examination alone. Therefore, ultrasound is unnecessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT of chest and abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered if there was suspicion of an underlying malignancy, such as renal cell carcinoma, which can rarely cause an isolated left-sided varicocele. However, the two-year history in this case makes such a diagnosis highly unlikely, and CT is not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration cytology\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate for a varicocele. This invasive procedure is typically used when there is suspicion of a solid mass or malignancy, which is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical exploration of the groin\u003C/strong\u003E or varicocelectomy might be considered if the patient had infertility or pain when standing or with Valsalva maneuver. However, this patient is asymptomatic, and surgery is not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn most cases, varicoceles do not require any intervention beyond reassurance. They are generally benign and do not cause significant problems. If the patient develops symptoms such as pain or if there are concerns about fertility, further evaluation or treatment may be considered. However, for this 60-year-old man with an asymptomatic varicocele, reassurance about the benign nature of the condition is the most appropriate management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Varicocele presents with abnormal dilatation and enlargement of the pampiniform plexus.","For most men, varicoceles do not require further investigation and the patient can be reassured.","Varicoceles are common, occurring in approximately 20% of the male population."],"references":["K\u00fchn AL, Scortegagna E, Nowitzki KM, Kim YH. Ultrasonography of the scrotum in adults. Ultrasonography. 2016 Jul;35(3):180-97. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4939719/","Leslie SW, Sajjad H, Siref LE. Varicocele. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2022. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448113/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84174"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1720"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19413"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19413"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpe